2026-04-16 12:25:42 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module internal series element between relay output contact and 12 V rail (e.g., incorrectly wired / wrong-value resistor or track)'] hypothesis_explanation='All tests show: \n- PSU output is a solid 12 V referenced to the external 0 V line.\n- Control module input sees the full 12 V correctly.\n- The relay coil is continuously energized and the contact resistance itself is essentially 0 Ω, and continuity from the contact output to the external + output cable is good.\n- Yet, when the relay is closed, the “downstream” side of the relay contact sits at only ~0.36 V, not at 12 V, even with the load module disconnected (no significant load).\n- Re-referencing measurements to the internal 0 V node confirmed that the 12 V rail and 0 V rail inside the control module are correct; the anomaly is only on the path from the internal 12 V node to the relay output when the relay is supposed to short them.\n- Ground-return integrity has already been checked and repaired/ruled out as a root cause.\n\nTherefore the only remaining consistent explanation is that there is an unintended series resistance or miswired / wrong-value component *in series between the 12 V input node and the relay output node* inside the control module. Under the very small current drawn by the control circuitry and measurement instrument, this element drops nearly the entire 12 V, leaving about 0.36 V at the relay output. This could be a misplaced or incorrect resistor, a PCB trace routed through a component that should not be there, or an internal wiring fault that inserts resistance where there should be a hard short.\n\nReplacing/repairing this internal series element (restoring a direct low-resistance path from the 12 V input node to the relay common contact) should restore a full 12 V at the control module output when the relay is closed, which will in turn allow the load module lamp to operate normally without the periodic dropouts caused by the effective undervoltage at its input.'
